grep -R "aerolit-bundle.yml\|Bundle manifest\|bundle manifest\|manifest" -n src README.md man packaging completions 2>/dev/null || true
grep -R "def .*bundle\|bundle validate\|validate_bundle\|doctor\|configure init\|initialize" -n src/aerolitctl 2>/dev/null || true
find src/aerolitctl -maxdepth 1 -type f -name "*.py" -print | sort

That will tell us exactly where the current warning lives and where the cleanest hook point is.

My expected file targets are probably:

src/aerolitctl/initialize.py
src/aerolitctl/bundle.py
src/aerolitctl/doctor.py
src/aerolitctl/paths.py or config.py, depending how paths are centralized

I would probably add a small new helper module, maybe:

src/aerolitctl/bundle_manifest.py

That keeps the manifest logic from getting jammed into initialize.py, bundle.py, and doctor.py separately.

The first version of the manifest should stay simple. Something like:

bundle_schema_version: 1
bundle_name: aerolit-bundle
created_by: aerolitctl
bundle_layout_version: 1
paths:
  collections_hub: collections-hub
  ansible_dir: collections-hub/ansible
  group_vars_all: collections-hub/ansible/group_vars/all
  repos: repos
  files: files
  extracted_isos: extracted_isos
  bootstrap: bootstrap.sh
  sync_preserve: collections-hub/.sync-preserve
  gitlab_ci: collections-hub/.gitlab-ci.yml
features:
  pxe_server: true
  ansible_controller: true
  nfs: true

I would not add checksums, ISO inventory, repo inventory, or generated timestamps yet unless you really want that now. Those make the manifest more powerful, but they also create more decisions and more ways for the file to become stale. For this first branch, the goal should be: “AeroLIT can create and validate its own bundle identity file.”

